I might offer a dissenting opinion to Zach's reply and say that I'm generally not in favor of this change.  I looked at your implementation (that you linked to above), and I think your goal is to get data into Splunk via the HTTP Event Collector in general; you don't appear to actually need a logger at all.  https://github.com/zach-taylor/splunk_handler/pull/13 is another example of where what you really needed was a generic sender class, not a logger that does best-effort transmission and swallows errors (like, quite literally - this application overrides the loggers for itself, urllib3, and requests).

I would strongly recommend just lifting the relevant code and creating your own Splunk HEC sender class using this one as a reference.  This project is licensed MIT; you can grab and reuse whatever code you want however you want :)  But I fear you are going down a road that is going to cause you far more headaches than it's worth.

