@3kwa The problems with setup_requires basically boil down to the fact it uses easy_install, not pip. easy_install uses a different configuration file, and being a legacy thing doesn't support the full range of pip operations, like installing wheels and (I think) supporting fancy features like environment markers. It seems to work okay for cython and jinja2, though, and it's as far as I know the only real option when third party code is needed in setup.py.

@grgsrs Yes, if you want to manually generate the C code before building, then we can get rid of both jinja2 and cython as setup dependencies. It's kind of a hassle, though, in that you need to think about it every time, no?

The Cython docs state: 

> It is strongly recommended that you distribute the generated .c files as well as your Cython sources, so that users can install your module without needing to have Cython available.

but Pyrobuf has Cython as a runtime dependency anyway, so Cython needs to be available to install in any case. Some time can be saved by pre-generating them (less work in setup.py), I guess, but then again whenever there is a Cython update (it gets better/faster or more compatible with say PyPy) you will need to regenerate and repack the .c sources.

I can push a different branch if you want to see what I'm suggesting (wrapping cythonize in a command). So, in a command, I generate the Cython sources (using jinja), then call cythonize on that and assign the result to distribution.ext_modules. Since I do this in the overriden install command, this happens after the setup deps are fetched.

