@jsignell I think the issue is that the original gridded data is not defined with a projection, rather it is a set of points with Cartesian distances from a given latitude, longitude and altitude.  I've had discussions over if this type of gridded data has a associated map projection which have not been conclusive.  If such data does have an associated projection it would be a Azimuthal Equidistant projection not a Lambert Conformal.  

The `RadarMapDisplay` class makes no assumption about the projection to associate with the gridded data.  It leave it to the user to specify the map projection.  Lambert Conformal ('lcc') is default projection but only because some default is needed.  Basemap then can be used to transform the gridded Cartesian data into this projection.

   I think something similar can be done with Cartopy, leave the specification of the projection entirely to the user and using Lambert Conformal only as the default which gets entirely overridden when a user specifies a different projection.  Moving the creation of LambertConformal projection into the `if projection is None` block will solve some of this but the other uses of `self.proj` need to be worked out.

